The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, May 12, 2004 				 Canon spotlight on digital imaging 
 A STAFF REPORTER				 	 Alok Bharadwaj in Calcutta on Tuesday. A Telegraph picture																								Calcutta, May 11: Canon India hopes to clock a 59 per cent growth in its digital imaging business and also top the Rs 100-crore revenue mark by the end of the year.																								Of the Rs 270-crore overall revenue target for 2004, the digital imaging business is expected to contribute Rs 102 crore, said Alok Bharadwaj, DGM, consumer imaging and information division and volume products. Focus will be on home entertainment and the printing segment.																								The company today unveiled seven digicams, three digital camcorders, two projectors, two inkjet printers and two all-in-one products as part of its strategy to offer a complete digital imaging solution.																								Canon plans to achieve a turnover of Rs 700 crore by 2007 and a 30 per cent market share in digital imaging products. These include laser and photo printers, digicams, digital camcorders, LCD projectors and consumables.																								The digicam market alone is expected to grow 400 per cent to touch 70 million units by 2007. Around 45,000 units are expected to be sold this fiscal, said Bharadwaj.																								With 80 million camera phones expected to be sold worldwide, the photo printing business is another area that the company will actively focus on, he added. 
